      <hedline>
        <hl1>TV SOCCER TALKS END</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Alan Cowell</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Cowell, Alan</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Cable TV provider NTL Inc fails to strike deal with Premiership soccer league of England to broadcast pay-per-view games next three years (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The cable TV provider NTL Inc. failed to strike a deal with the Premiership soccer league of England to broadcast pay-per-view games the next three years. NTL, which has 3.4 million customers in Britain and Ireland and is financially backed by France Telecom and Microsoft, said it had offered $447 million for the rights to broadcast 40 pay-per-view games a year. The 20-team Premiership League, which includes Manchester United and other top teams, is Britain's richest league.</p>
        <p>Alan Cowell</p>
      </block>
